# ListMyNest — Backend Cursor Rules
# Always read README.md, PRD.md, TRD.md before starting any task.
# Reference them with @README.md @PRD.md @TRD.md in every new chat session.

## Project
You are building the ListMyNest Spring Boot backend — a REST API for a
mobile-first real estate discovery platform targeting Tier-3 Indian cities.

## Tech Stack
- Java 17, Spring Boot 3.2.3, Gradle
- Spring Data JPA + Hibernate (PostgreSQL via Supabase)
- Spring Security 6 + JWT (stateless, no sessions)
- Redis via Upstash (OTP hashes, rate limiting, view count buffer, cache)
- Flyway (database migrations — V1 through V11)
- MSG91 (OTP/SMS delivery, Sender ID: LSTNEST)
- Wati.io (WhatsApp inbound webhook + outbound templates)
- Firebase Admin SDK (FCM push notifications to agents)
- Google Maps Geocoding API (address → lat/lng on property creation)

## Package Structure
com.listmynest/
  controller/   → thin REST controllers, no business logic
  service/      → all business logic lives here
  repository/   → Spring Data JPA interfaces only
  model/        → JPA @Entity classes (UUID PKs, UTC timestamps, DB-level enums)
  dto/          → Java records for request/response (never expose entity directly)
  config/       → SecurityConfig, CorsConfig, RedisConfig, OpenApiConfig
  exception/    → GlobalExceptionHandler, AppException
  scheduler/    → @Scheduled jobs (PropertyLifecycle, ViewCountFlush, VisitReminder)

## Architecture Rules (NON-NEGOTIABLE)
1. Controllers must be THIN — validate input, call one service method, return DTO
2. GET /properties and GET /properties/{id} response DTOs must NEVER include
   seller_phone or agent_phone — use PublicPropertyDTO record that excludes them
3. Only GET /whatsapp/link/{propertyId} may return agent WA number —
   and ONLY after logging the lead via LeadService first
4. Call Now button dials agent phone, never seller phone
5. All admin actions must call AdminAuditService.log() — no exceptions
6. OTP hashes stored in Redis ONLY (never PostgreSQL)
7. Backend never handles file bytes — always use Supabase signed URLs
8. Flyway migration files: V{n}__{description}.sql — NEVER edit after creation

## Security Rules
- Buyers (anonymous): permit all GET /properties/**, POST /leads, POST /visits
- Buyer token (soft OTP): scope limited to /saved and /notify-me endpoints only
- Seller JWT: own listings CRUD only (validate ownership in service layer)
- Agent JWT: assigned leads/visits only (validate assignment in service layer)
- Admin JWT: all /admin/** + impersonation (8h expiry)
- Wati webhook: authenticated via X-Wati-Secret header only, NOT JWT
- Rate limits enforced in Redis before any OTP send (max 3/phone/hour)

## Redis Key Conventions
otp:{phone}                    TTL 300s   — seller/agent OTP hash
buyer_otp:{phone}              TTL 300s   — buyer soft OTP hash
otp_send_count:{phone}         TTL 3600s  — OTP send rate limit counter
prop_inactive_warn:{id}        TTL 1296000s — 30→45 day lifecycle flag
view_count:{property_id}       TTL 60s    — view count buffer (batch flush)
wa_rl:{session}:{prop_id}      TTL 3600s  — WhatsApp click rate limit
call_rl:{session}:{prop_id}    TTL 3600s  — Call click rate limit
visit_rl:{session}             TTL 86400s — Visit request rate limit

## Component Build Order (follow strictly — never skip ahead)
Phase A: DB migrations → Entity models → Repositories → Redis config → Security config
Phase B: AuthService + AuthController (seller/agent OTP + JWT)
         BuyerAuthService + BuyerAuthController (buyer soft OTP)
Phase C: PropertyService + PropertyController (CRUD, view count)
         AgentRoutingService (round-robin assignment)
         StorageService (Supabase signed URLs)
         GpsValidationService (Haversine check, soft flag >500m)
Phase D: LeadService + LeadController
         WhatsAppService (Wati webhook handler + template sender)
         VisitService + VisitController
         NotifyMeService + NotifyMeController
Phase E: SavedListingService + SavedListingController
Phase F: AdminService + AdminController
         AdminImpersonationController
         AdminAuditService
Phase G: PropertyLifecycleScheduler (daily 8AM)
         ViewCountFlushScheduler (every 60s)
         VisitReminderScheduler (FCM 1hr before visit)

## DTO Rules
- All response DTOs must be Java records
- PublicPropertyDTO: NEVER include seller_phone, agent_phone, seller_id
- Request DTOs: use Bean Validation annotations (@NotNull, @Size, @Pattern)
- Page responses: wrap in a PageResponse<T> record with { content, page, size, total }

## Testing Requirements
- JUnit 5 + Mockito for all service layer tests (target 80%+ coverage)
- @MockitoBean for Spring context tests
- Every scheduler must have boundary-condition unit tests
- GpsValidationService: test at exactly 500m, 499m, 501m boundaries
- PropertyLifecycleScheduler: test 29-day (no action), 30-day (warn), 45-day (inactive)
